'''Drew Beasley''' (born 2001) is a [[pre-teen]] American actor working in television, film, theater, and commercials. He is also a published author.

== Acting and voice acting ==
{{BLP sources section|date=September 2013}}
Beasley has appeared in the films ''[[Shutter Island]]'' (directed by [[Martin Scorsese]]), ''[[The Private Lives of Pippa Lee]]'' (directed by [[Rebecca Miller]] and starring [[Robin Wright]]), ''Somebody<U+2019>s Hero'' (directed by [[Darin Beckstead]]), and ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man 2]]'' (directed by [[Marc Webb]]). In 2011 he portrayed Dick in the short ''Tommy's Pumpkin'' (directed by Alex Halpern).

On television, Beasley had a recurring role (as Erickson) in the dramatic series ''[[Damages (TV series)|Damages]]'', has appeared periodically on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', guested on ''[[Late Night with Jimmy Fallon]]'', and appeared in the programs ''[[Rescue Me (U.S. TV series)|Rescue Me]]'',<ref>[http://archive.is/20130125100659/http://www.hollywood.com/celebrity/6301255/Drew_Beasley_Credits Hollywood.com Beasley appears as "David" in Rescue Me]{{dead link|date=September 2013}}</ref> ''[[Blue Bloods (TV series)|Blue Bloods]]'',<ref>[http://www.thefutoncritic.com/listings/20120120cbs01 ''Blue Bloods'': "The Job" (aired February 3, 2012)]</ref> and ''[[White Collar (TV series)|White Collar]]''. He portrayed Charlie Garretti in the brief run of the CBS legal drama ''[[Made in Jersey]]''. In 2014 he portrayed Quinton in the TV series ''[[Unforgettable (2011 TV series)|Unforgettable]]''.

He has contributed [[voiceovers]] to the [[Nickelodeon]] series ''[[Dora the Explorer]]'' (as Pinto the Horse), ''[[Wonder Pets]]'', and ''[[Are You Ready? (TV series)|Are You Ready?]]''

Beasley has appeared in (or done voiceovers for) [[television commercials|television]] and [[radio commercials|radio]] commercials for [[Walmart]], [[Jif peanut butter]], [[Olive Garden]], [[Smuckers]], [[Hasbro]], [[Tetley Tea]], [[Band-Aids]], [[LongHorn Steakhouse]], [[Nestl<U+00E9> Purina PetCare Company|Purina]], [[SeaWorld]], [[Mercedes-Benz]], and other products and sponsors.

== Other work ==
At the age of ten, Beasley wrote and published ''Growing Up ... With Jack''. The book encourages positive behavior around young children with [[special needs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/01/us/young-writers-find-a-devoted-publisher-thanks-mom-and-dad.html|title=Young Writers Dazzle Publisher (Mom and Dad)|work=New York Times|date=2012-03-31|first=Elissa|last=Gootman|accessdate=2013-09-15}}</ref>

== Personal life ==
Beasley is currently enrolled at the [[Professional Children's School]] in Manhattan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.drewbeasley.com|title=Drew Beasley|year=2012|publisher=Drewbeasley.com|accessdate=2013-03-31}}</ref>

